rath: Designing and Publishing Isotype Books for Children -- t30 Building Feminist Institutions: Women in Distribution, the Feminist Press and Cultures of Small Press Circulation -- t31 Virago Modern Classics: The Making of a Reprint Series -- t32 Murder at The Women’s Press: Transnational Accomplices and the Feminist Crime Scene -- t33 Shifting Agency: Feminist Publishing Collectives in Aotearoa New Zealand -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex -- tPlate0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores the diversity of women’s work in transatlantic and continental publishing across the twentieth-centuryThe first international edited collection to explore women’s diverse work in book and magazine publishing in the twentieth century Specially commissioned, archivally-rich chapters from leading established and early-careers scholars, edited by an international research team Transatlantic and European/continental in focus, going beyond the Anglosphere, and modelling the best new comparative work in global print culturesCuts across aesthetic divisions in twentieth-century literary history and bridges the gap in understandings of women’s contributions to publishing from first to second and third/fourth wave feminismsIncludes interviews with 8 contemporary women in publishing, plus new oral history researchWomen’s creative labour in publishing has often been overlooked. This book draws on dynamic new work in feminist book history and publishing studies to offer the first comparative collection exploring women’s diverse, deeply embedded work in modern publishing. Highlighting the value of networks, collaboration, and archives, the companion sets out new ways of reading women’s contributions to the production and circulation of global print cultures. With an international, intergenerational set of contributors using diverse methodologies, essays explore women working in publishing transatlantically, on the continent, and beyond the Anglosphere. The book combines new work on high-profile women publishers and editors alongside analysis of women’s work as translators, illustrators, booksellers, advertisers, patrons, and publisher’s readers; complemented by new oral histories and interviews with leading women in publishing today. The first collection of its kind, the companion helps establish and shape a thriving new research field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh1 aBattershill, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBattershill, Claire, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBheacháin, Caoilfhionn Ní, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBird, Hazel Sheeky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBold, Melanie Ramdarshan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCesana, Roberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDerrick, Stephanie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernández, Pura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFollacchio, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranco, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeywood, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeywood, Sophie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHicok, Bethany, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollis, Catherine W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutton, Clar